What is HTTP?

HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) is the protocol used for communication between web clients (browsers) and web servers.
It defines how requests and responses are structured when accessing websites.

E.g.:

Browser requests a webpage
Server sends back the webpage content
How HTTP Works

When you visit a website:

1.Your browser sends an HTTP request to a server
2.The server processes the request
3.The server sends back an HTTP response
4.Your browser renders the content (HTML, CSS, JS)

HTTP Request Structure
An HTTP request contains:

Method (GET, POST, etc.)
URL / Path (e.g. /login)
Headers (extra metadata like browser type)
Optional body (data sent to server)

Common HTTP Methods:
GET → retrieve data
POST → send data
PUT → update data
DELETE → remove data

HTTP Response Structure
A server response includes:

Status code
Headers
Body (actual content)
Common Status Codes
200 → OK (success)
301 → Redirect
400 → Bad request
401 → Unauthorized
403 → Forbidden
404 → Not found
500 → Server error

Stateless Protocol
HTTP is stateless, meaning:

Each request is independent
The server does not remember previous requests by default

To maintain sessions, websites use:

Cookies
Sessions
Tokens

HTTP vs HTTPS:

HTTP:
Not encrypted
Data sent in plaintext
Vulnerable to interception

HTTPS:
Encrypted using TLS
Protects confidentiality and integrity
Verifies server identity using certificates

Why HTTP Matters in Cybersecurity
HTTP is commonly targeted because it handles:

Login credentials
Session tokens
Sensitive user data

Attackers may exploit HTTP traffic through:

Man-in-the-middle attacks
Session hijacking
Credential theft

Key Takeaways:
HTTP is the protocol used for web communication.
It uses requests and responses between browser and server.
Common methods include GET and POST.
Status codes indicate request results.
HTTPS adds encryption and security.
